To create a Visual Studio Code extension that opens a Google search page within the VS Code environment, we can use the `WebView` panel feature which allows you to display web content in a special kind of editor panel.

Below are simplified versions of `extension.ts` and `package.json` files for such an extension.

First, create your `package.json`:

```json
{
  "name": "google-in-vscode",
  "displayName": "Google in VSCode",
  "description": "Open Google search inside VS Code",
  "version": "0.0.1",
  "publisher": "your-name-here",
  "engines": {
    "vscode": "^1.58.0"
  },
  "categories": ["Other"],
  "activationEvents": ["onCommand:googleInVscode.search"],
  "main": "./out/extension.js",
  "contributes": {
    "commands": [
      {
        "command": "googleInVscode.search",
        "title": "Search with Google"
      }
    ]
  },
  "scripts": {
    "vscode:prepublish": "tsc -p ./",
    "compile": "tsc -watch -p ./",
    "postinstall": "node ./node_modules/vscode/bin/install"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "@types/node": "^14.14.37",
    "@types/vscode": "^1.58.0",
    "typescript": "^4.2.4",
    "vscode": "^1.1.37"
  }
}
```

Next, create your `extension.ts` file:

```typescript
import * as vscode from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
  let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('googleInVscode.search', () => {
    // Create and show a new webview panel
    const panel = vscode.window.createWebviewPanel(
      'googleSearch', // Identifies the type of the webview. Used internally
      'Google Search', // Title of the panel displayed to the user
      vscode.ViewColumn.One, // Editor column to show the new webview panel in.
      {} // Webview options.
    );

    // And set its HTML content
    panel.webview.html = getWebviewContent();
  });

  context.subscriptions.push(disposable);
}

function getWebviewContent() {
  // Return HTML content for Google Search (simple version)
  // Note that webviews must use HTTPS for all resources, like scripts and styles.
  return `
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html lang="en">
    <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
      <title>Google Search</title>
    </head>
    <body>
      <iframe src="https://www.google.com/webhp?igu=1" frameborder="0" style="width:100%;height:100vh;"></iframe>
    </body>
    </html>`;
}

export function deactivate() {}
```

To install your extension locally, you will need to compile your TypeScript code, package it, and install it into VSCode. Here are some steps:

1. Run `npm install` to install the required dependencies and types.
2. Run `npm run compile` to compile your TypeScript to JavaScript.
3. Press `F5` to run your extension in a new Extension Development Host window.
4. Execute your command from the Command Palette (Ctrl+Shift+P) by typing "Search with Google".
5. A panel will open in VSCode with Google search inside as an iframe.

Remember that extension development and in particular dealing with webviews can be quite complex, and issues like security and content policy must be considered. This is a basic example, in a real-world situation you would need to follow best practices for secure coding in Visual Studio Code extensions.

To create a Visual Studio Code extension that leverages a different approach (i.e., not using the WebView panel feature) to open a Google search within VS Code, you can create a command that opens the user's default web browser to the Google homepage.

Here are the modified `extension.ts` and `package.json` files:

`package.json`:

```json
{
  "name": "google-in-vscode",
  "displayName": "Google in VSCode",
  "description": "Open Google search in your default browser from VS Code",
  "version": "0.0.1",
  "publisher": "your-name-here",
  "engines": {
    "vscode": "^1.58.0"
  },
  "categories": ["Other"],
  "activationEvents": ["onCommand:googleInVscode.openGoogle"],
  "main": "./out/extension.js",
  "contributes": {
    "commands": [
      {
        "command": "googleInVscode.openGoogle",
        "title": "Open Google"
      }
    ]
  },
  "scripts": {
    "vscode:prepublish": "tsc -p ./",
    "compile": "tsc -watch -p ./",
    "postinstall": "node ./node_modules/vscode/bin/install"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "@types/node": "^14.14.37",
    "@types/vscode": "^1.58.0",
    "typescript": "^4.2.4",
    "vscode": "^1.1.37"
  }
}
```

`extension.ts`:

```typescript
import * as vscode from 'vscode';
import * as open from 'open';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
  let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('googleInVscode.openGoogle', () => {
    // Open the default web browser to the Google homepage
    open('https://www.google.com').catch((err) => {
      vscode.window.showErrorMessage('Failed to open Google: ' + err);
    });
  });

  context.subscriptions.push(disposable);
}

export function deactivate() {}
```

In this `extension.ts` example, we are using the `open` package to open the default web browser. This package is not included by default, so you will need to install it. You can install it using the following command:

```bash
npm install open
```

Also, you will need to add `open` to your dependencies in `package.json`:

```json
"dependencies": {
  "open": "^7.3.0"
}
```

Make sure you run the following commands during your development:

1. Run `npm install` to install all the required dependencies.
2. Run `npm run compile` to compile your TypeScript to JavaScript.
3. Press `F5` to start debugging your extension in an Extension Development Host window.

After making sure the extension works as expected, you can then package it to be published on the VS Code Extensions Marketplace or distribute it manually. Use the `vsce` command-line tool to package and publish your extension:

```bash
npm install -g vsce
vsce package
```

The `vsce package` command will generate a `.vsix` file for your extension, which can be installed into VS Code.

